nstitutional amend\nment which would allow Irene a \u201cthree\ncounty to* n\u201d to decide which county it\nwanted to become a part of and wipe\nout the disadvantages of its citizens\ngoing into three different counties to\nvote. This had been amended to cover\na number of other features and after\nlighting them over for a long and loudly\nWaged verbal contest some one suggest\ned that the session was trying to put too\nmuch legislation into a constitutional\namendment an put the whole matter\nover for further consideration after il\nhad been pared down to reul constitu\ntional provisions.\nR 0. Richards, who evidently feels\nthat the legislature will not enact hit\nnew measures already has petitions out\n:o place them upon a referendum ballot\nit the m electi n, luit appeared before\nthe 11 use committee on temperance\nFriday evening in advocacy of his view\n.hat the \u201clt d test of moral citizenship\ncan only be rightly shown by restoring\nwine, beer and braudy to this state;\u201d\nwhich is the whole sum and substance\nd Ins \u201cmoral citizenship bill\u201d when the\nipeitluities are pared away. He is\npositive m hi- statement that lie has the\nonly real system of testing moral citi\nzenship, and to be certain that lie will\nget his ideas before the people be will\ninitiate ins law along with one abolish\ning the state sheriff at the next elec\ntion.\nIhe new compulsory educational bill\nis provided with real \u201cteeth\u201d as com\npared with any former bill along that\nline. Under old laws a certain number\nof weeks schooling was required in each\nyear. Under the present bill which has\npassed the House it is for the full school\nyear in the district in which the child\nlives Child means anyone between\neight and seventeen years of age inclu\nsive. If those in control of any such\nchild fails to provide this schooling the\npenalty upon such person is a tine of not\nless than ten dollars and not more than\n?25 for the hist offense, and a tine of not\ncss than Silo nor more than fob for any\nsubsequent offense, w ith a jail sentence\nfur good measure if considered advis\nable. An attempt to amend to allow\nfarm children to be out from April let\nto November Ist to help iu farm work\ndid not get anywhere, and was decided\nly defeated, and the schooling required\nis the full term with no variations before\nor after ttie term.\nlhe session has been getting down to\ngrind of business this week, and has be\ngun to turn out bills as well as pouring\nnew ones into the hopper. Among the\nnew \"emue lulls by black Hills people\nh one by (iuilfoyle, of Fall River, plac\ning the Custer State l\u2019ark Game Sanctu\nary under the control of the State Park\nboard and providing for the protection\nif game animals within the Park, and\nby Lrskine, of Meade, appropriating\nmoney to assist in maintaining the state\nnurses ir.amining board, aud another\nto provide lor maintenance of kinder\ngartens m independent and consolidated\nschool districts, aud to prevent the kill\ning of deer in this state for a period of\nthree years from the date of ttie passage\nof the law by Moner protecting the\nbeds and bars of navigable streams of\nthe state.\n.New bills by Black Mills members in\nthe Mouse are by Mayo, of Lawrence,\nrelating to regulation of contracts by\nmunicipal corporations; Kneeland, of\nCuster, lixmg the place of assessment of\nrailway ami bridge Companies; by Bar\nker, of Lawrence, giving women the\nright ol jury service, legitimatizing\nchildren burn out ol wedlock, and regu\nlating proot nt acknowledgement ol in\nstruments, Clark, of Lawrence, regulat\ning high ways superintendents; Warren,\nol Lawrence, ncreasiug publication fees\nfor delinquent tax sale uolices; Forney,\nof Fall liiver, regulating admission to\nthe state soldieis home.\nIn the discussion over the Aiseth\nle.-olutiou to close the session February\n15Mh, Senator Liuilfoyle, of Fall Kiver,\nwasoueofthe advocates of the resolu\ntion on the ground that there is too\nmuch rather than too little legislation,\nbut the resolution failed to go across.\nThe hill compelling attendance in the\npublic scb >o's during the full term start\ned considerable discussion aud when\nHartling, of Hutchinson, supported the\namendment to allow farm children to\nbe eicused from April Ist to Not ember\nIst for farm work, Warren, of Law\nrence, opposed the amendment and\nwanted to know if Hutchinson county\nfarmers were raising iuidren or farm\nmachinery.\nThe state game and fish protective\nassociation has gone or. it ml in favor\nof a hill to prohibit tin- k iing of does\nby deer hunters, and when tins bill was\ncalled up Senator Cock, f butte, asked\nthat it go over unti ai ther bill iu\npreparation came in an it they be\nconsidered together, flit- new bill is\nby Krskine, of Meade, i. (interest\nto all the black Hil Is count.i-s, as it pro\nhibits the killing of her within the\nslate for three years, with i penalty f a\ndue of not less than t u more than\n#oOO and imprisonment in tho count)\njail not less than thir y days no more\nthan six months. Tin ail penalty be\ning to put more force back ot the law\nSeuator Erskine says that Hie real sports\nmen are for the bill. Ibe uew meisuit\ncarries a specific prov isi n tli.d no li\ncenses shall be issued to c m bun;*-i\nwithin the limit prescribed ,u b\nregardless ot any other provision it ti e\nstatute to the contrary. Fins me.-me\nis put up on the plea that uu c-- liastn\nictiou is taken deer hti .tit gw i >n\nlieu thing of the past iu''ie li ick II\npractically the only dt-ei .-.ectim the\nstate.\nIK TV 1\".\n\nHLV r W. S. HAKfEB TEN DE I\nItEaIUN ATiO.N A s PA Vi OH\nIt is w ith deep regret that the people\nof Custer learn of the te.-unu\u2019i >u -i\nS. Harper, pastor of tire migregiitmmi\nChurch, said resignation not ne i-.-.-ardy\nur t.ike effect until the end >f the p i-i r\nal year, May, 1921. While p.i-t >i the\nCongregational oliurch iu a I\u25a0 i\u25a0\u25a0 t -en-t\nMr. Harper has looked up- n t >'l\ncommunity as a parish Mi iiv after\ncoining to the county lie was a; p anted\non the Local board o! 1 vemptmn i r\nCuster rrunty ami served during the\nwar in that capacity. When the Red\nCross was organized Mr. liar; r be. tme\nhairmun and later became tbe cha r\nman of the Home Service department\nwhich be still holds. During the vvm\nind up to the present time m than\nthousand letters have been wr it ten in\nthe interest of the soldn-is ai d the\nclaims before the government s ireely\nan ex-Service man in the intv who\nhas nut had work done iu the Horn*\nService department. Mr. Harper h.i\nueeri President of the board >f 1 dues\ntion for nearly three years, and in com\nmon with the other mein\u2019n is of the\nboard Iras assisted in bringing Custer\nschools to its present working basis, arid\nsuccess.\nA year ago Mr. Harper was elected\nsecretary of the commercial club and\nhas been a Booster for the community\ntbe past year, ae.-i.sti .g it pur n. ,nt\nWhat Would Lincoln and Washington Say?\nI\nt This month, in celebrating the birthdays of Lincoln and Wash\nington, well may we consider what their comment might be today\nregi rding prevailing conditions in America.\nRecalling the same logic of the immortal Lincoln, can not we\nima jine him very emphatically saying, \u201cThe time for talk has passed.\nThe time to act has come. Knowing that the fundamental principles j\nunderlying the Nation\u2019s business are sound, we must practice the good\nsense which directs each and every member of our great national\nfam ly to quickly, honestly and promptly contribute his full share to-\nward the return to normal conditions.\u201d\n\nAnd is it not possible that Washington might say, \u201cWe must stop\nlyin j, not only to each other but to ourselves, understanding that the\ngreatest good for the greatest number depends upon honestly meet-\ning jur individual responsibilities one to the other.\u201d\nThe officers and directors of this bank are convinced that we\nare pointed toward a slow but nevertheless sure improvement in fi-\n1 nancial, industrial and agricultural conditions. The one way to has-\nJ ten the return of prosperity lies in the active co-operation between\nall the interests involved and in the honest rendering of the service\nfor which each of us is responsible.\n\nWe are ready at all times to extend a willing and considerate\nbanking service which we intend shall be helpful to the greatest possi-\nble degree in promoting the welfare of this community so that the\nj community in turn, may meet its responsibility to the community at\nlarge.\nj\nCUSTER COUNTY BANK\nCUSTER, SOUTH DAKOTA\nHOUSE BILL NO. 132\nRelating to Plan of Assessment of Rati\nroads. Gravel and Logging Roads\nHas Passed House\nHouse Bil No. 132, introduced bj\nRepresentative K net-laud, panned the\nhouse last Monday. It amends section\n6077 of the \">u li Dakota revised Code\nof 1919, and correct# one feature of thv\nold law which pr >vides that such roads\nmust tie taxed at the principal p ace ol\nbusiness of the owner instead of in the\ntow u,city or county, w here Hie buildings\ntrucks, an 1 appurtenances arc l ie..ted.\nFollowing is a copy ol the bill:\nbe enacted by the Legi-lat ire of the\n\"late of .\u2022south Dakota, that section \u00ab>\u00ab-77\nol the South Dakota Revised Code o\n1919 tie and the same is hereby amend\ned to read as follows:\nSection <ih77 Street Railway and\ndirer Companies. The trac k, road or\nbridge, and tire equipment and uppurt\nnances thereunto nging: or any\nrailroad, street railway, plank road,\ngravel road, logging i 01, turnpike or\n.ridge company, m >1 any person or\n-.operation owning and using any such\n:racks; roads oi hi. as one of the\nfacilities for the trau-.n tmn of its busi\nic.-s, when such track, r.iid \u00bbr bridge\nies wholly wittiin -ne cmmtv, shall he\nassessed in the county, city, town or\ndistrict were such tic r ..id or bridge\nand the uppurtenau \u2019es thereto arc locat\ned